description.text:
Oversized bottle cap with Vault boy.

You can print this in multiple colors on most printers with single extruder!

The Vault boy is designed in multiple layers (heights). By changing filament at the correct height, you can print it in multiple colors.

I've made a video describing the process and how to easily modify your gcode using Prusa's ColorPrint app:
https://youtu.be/KsbE2vEzS7U

Here are the heights for the filament changes (printing at 0,1mm layer height):

  • Start with silver or any base color you want for the bottle cap

  • At 11,0mm switch to red for the top color of the bottle cap

  • At 16,2mm switch to skin color

  • At 16,5mm switch to the yellow "T" section on the shirt

  • At 16,7mm switch to blue for the shirt

  • At 16,9mm switch to yellow for the hairs

  • At 17,1mm switch to black for the outline

You will have to manually paint the white area in the mouth (or leave it as red). It's not enough to warrant an entire layer by itself.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IS2uS_aWTHw Turn almost anything into a speaker with a bone conductor transducer and Adafruit's TPA audio amplifier. If your next project needs some sound, a bone conductor transducer will have you experimenting with all sorts of objects. If you've ever wired a speaker system before, you'll find this DIY electronics project is fun and easy! This incredible speaker does not have a moving cone like most speakers you've seen, instead, a small metal rod is wrapped with the voice coil. When current is pulsed through the coil, the magnetic field causes a piece of metal to expand and contract - if pressed against a flat surface or cavity it turns it into a speaker! Tools & Supplies
Soldering Iron
Wire Strippers
3D Printer Parts
Bone Conductor Transducer
150mAh Lithium Ion Polymer Battery
Stereo Headphone Jack
Slide Switch
JST Battery Ext. Cable

Check out the full tutorial on the Adafruit Learning System The enclosure is a three piece design that snap-fit together. The bonebox-top.stl part houses the slide switch and audio input jack. The bonebox-case.stl part houses the amplifier and lithium polymer battery. The bonebox-bottom.stl part houses the bone conductor transducer exposing the vibrating metal piece but is secured in place with built in clips on the bottom part. The parts are optimized to slice with MakerWare and printed using PLA with no raft or support material.

title: GoPro mount for drop ceiling
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Thingiverse almost always has what you need - and if not, it's usually got what you need to build what you're looking for. We've got folks coming in to clean our datacenter and we were saying it'd be funny to set up a time lapse. I had the GoPro, and probably could have rigged something up with the mounts I've got on hand, but decided it'd be more fun to make what I needed.

I've got two versions of the same model, one with and one without supports I added in MeshMixer. I printed both on my Monoprice Mini and found the supported one to be slightly better end result.

Printer:

Monoprice Mini v2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.131

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Printed with no brim and 2 shells with 20% infill and it seems plenty strong, especially since drop ceilings aren't generally subject to big drops and vibration. If you're in California, you may wish to print it thicker.

Step 1: See if anyone else made one

Uh... it's a GoPro mount for a drop ceiling. If anything says "action camera" less than drop ceilings, I'm unsure what. OOH wait cube wall GoPro mount (which gives me an idea)

Anyhow, no, nobody else made one - that I could find.

Step 2: Find parts that do what you need individually.

Easy peasy - GoPro mounts are a dime a dozen around here, and there's a surprising amount of drop ceiling clips. I found this GoPro mount for an SLR hot shoe and this drop ceiling clip for running cables which both looked like exactly what I needed.

Step 3: Mashup and make your part

I used MeshMixer to put the two parts together, lined things up, did a few plane cuts, and tried a boolean join. Well, MeshMixer seems to have a different idea of the results of a boolean join than I do, and the resulting part would have been an excellent low-poly modern art piece, but no longer looked like the parts that I started with. I guess I need to learn how to do that a little better. Instead, I combined the two parts into one solid, and that worked, although it messed up some of the edges. Tried printing that only to find out that I had created a 50MB STL file. That might be a wee bit more detail than absolutely necessary, so I remeshed it down to the current size.

description.text:
Although I am reluctant to promote the idea that “money grows on trees”, my wife for years has given our young nephews and nieces miniature Christmas trees with rolled up $2 bills tied to the branches. Since I am a retired product design engineer that has recently gotten into 3D printing, she asked if I could design some small ornaments that would hold $1 coins that could be hung on the small tree as a variation on the traditional money tree.

I came up with a star and a bell that I printed in gold, a snow flake, snowman and angel that I printed in white, a Christmas tree and holy leaf that I printed in green and several traditional ornaments I printed in red. I designed the coin holders for a US $1 coin which is 1.047” (26.7mm) in diameter, but the parts could be scaled in the slicer to accommodate most any round coin that is 20mm to 30mm in diameter. I have included a snow flake that I designed to hold the US Kennedy half dollar coin and a “bow” to hold paper money.

I use the Craftware slicer which I think is the best I have found.

description.text:
This is a paddle shifter design that I made for my SAE Formula team. We wanted to replace the shifting buttons on the steering wheel with something more intuitive so the driver wouldn't have to "look" for the buttons while driving. My design uses two magnets for the detente force and a lever actuated limit switch for signal transfer along with some McMaster hardware. Currently the magnets are N35 but if you want harder detente the linked website has the same magnets going up to N50. We printed it in ABS but PLA would probably hold up just fine. Enjoy!

comments.text: Those small, detailed spiky bits seem like your issue.  When you unload the filament you can probably see a notch carved out of the filament by the wheel.  All that small detail leads to lots of retracting and advancing, which can cause the filament to get too hot and soft, since it spends more time near the heated nozzle.  Try cooling the extruder with a fan blowing towards the top where the filament enters.  Could try reducing print temp too, but that has not worked for me like the fan does.  Hope that helps.

Some objects here, notably a few models of women here, do not have a flat bottom. Now I will concede that I prefer women who don't have a flat bottom, but if you want to 3d print them this is difficult.

The slanted bottom happens on the "pink panther woman" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1216 and the "venus bust" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24188 . I find that loading such models into cad programs and then intersecting with a cube or something like that is not possible. (I stopped trying after freecad errored out with an hour and a half of CPU time already spent on the conversions). It should be possible with more advanced CAD programs. Compile the program. I use gcc -Wall -O2 clipstl.c -o clipstl . Run the program with the STL file as an argument. It will tell you the ranges of the X, Y and Z coordinates. Now you can clip off a small portion of your model by adding to your commandline minz and then a number slightly larger than the minz in your model. The program will spit out the new STL on stdout. Redirect to a file. Bugs and restrictions: ASCII stl is not supported. The program is quite simplistic: It simply clips off the coordinates of vertices that lie outside the wanted region. If your object is not convex in the area you're clipping the clipping will cause overlapping triangles. This could confuse slicers. The program doesn't touch the normal vector. As it changes one coordinate, it should adjust the normal vector. The normal vector is used (if at all) to determine what is IN and what is OUTside the object. This will still work, even though the vector is not normal to the triangle. I don't know why Thiniverse shows the download "clipstl.c" as "lipstl".

title: Desktop Christmas Tree with LED star

description.text:
The Desktop Christmas Tree is a great DIY project that only requires the print and an LED, some wires and a CR32 watch battery. The wires and battery are not needed if you do not intend on lighting the LED.

For more information on this and other builds check out our blog section at:
https://www.gadgetsthatgo.com/blogs/how-to

4mm

20% +

Assembly

  1. Connect the tree trunks with the four circular branches in between arranged incrementally by size so that the largest is on the bottom trunk and the smallest on the top.

  2. Connect the tree top section above the last tree trunk.

  3. Slide an LED into the star and solder the ends to two wires that will protrude from each end of the trunk by at least a few inches.

  4. Slide both wires through top on through the bottom and through the first base piece attaching it to the bottom of the last tree trunk after the wire passes through.

  5. To keep everything compact, I have used a CR32 watch battery that fits between the bases. After removing the plastic covering around the last half inch of wire run one wire above the battery and run the second wire into the channel on the bottom base under the battery. Close the connection by attaching the bottom base to the top and the Christmas tree star should light up for you.

description.text:
Decorate your room with the ultimate Dr. Who accessory ... a TARDIS curtain pull back!

It is built from two printed parts - the TARDIS and a connector. There are three connectors to choose from - a left rod, a right rod, and a special one that might connect to an existing rod if you have one (made specifically for ones we had). You connect the parts by simply sliding the rod/mount onto the TARDIS using the slot on the back.

I found dimensions of a "real" TARDIS online from some old, scanned BBC blueprints, and used those to create this scaled model. The native size is somewhat large (2.75 inches by 7 inches) but looks great against the size of a regular window (see pictures). You can always change size when printing, though make sure you size all the parts at the same ratio, or they won't fit together.

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Medium (.25mm or so works nice)

Infill:

20%

Notes:

All STL files are oriented in the correct direction for printing without supports. You need one TARDIS plus one of the three mounts. One mount, the small vertical one (and yes, you print it vertically to avoid supports), is for connecting to an existing threaded curtain pull back, if you happen to have one that fits it. Otherwise, just use the left or right rod and you are good to go!

If you are using the rods, you will need two screws to mount them to the wall. If using the mount and your existing rod, then you just need the one screw from the mount to the rod. Either way, the TARDIS connects to the rod/mount without any additional hardware.

I printed the TARDIS using blue glow-in-the-dark PLA ... pretty cool at night!

description.text:
After trying 2 of the existing cases for the TS-100 soldering irons I was a bit underwhelmed with how bulky they were and how fragile the hinges turned out to be. Also I did not manage to print one in PETG that would close and stay closed.

That is why I made my own as an exercise in learning IceSL. The curved edges make it feel a lot more handy than the other cases - also the zipper securely closes it without the fragility that small hinges have.

A downside however is that the stitching the zipper will take a while. The zipper I used was a 5mm zipper but a 3mm zipper should work just as well.

The STLs were rendered by IceSL so they are a bit "weird" and stepped in .2mm. This is also why the files are this large. If you look at them zoomed in you will see what I mean.

You should print in .2 resolution as a minimum since a finer resolution won't get you anything.

A warning: Superglueing the zipper will turn the cloth parts hard and the glue will soak into the cloth thus affecting a large part of it. This will prevent the zipper from working well. You will either have to be extremely careful or stitch the zipper.

Also since this is the first time making a model in LUA with IceSL the code is a bit bad and I won't release it ;)

Printer:

DIY Prusa i3 clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

30%

Notes:

The model was made with very thin walls and thus will only take about 40g of PETG to print.

Again don't print in less than .2 - the way IceSL rendered the .STL files means it won't get you anything quality-wise.
Be prepared to spend an hour or two on sowing the zipper in. Nylon-thread recommended.

The white "TS-100" font effect is made by filling the groves with white acrylic paint and then wiping off the excess.

This is a 28mm scale rpg miniature that I designed using the Desktophero beta.

She is a human necromancer holding a skull and a book. I recommend printing on her back an then gluing her to the included base. If you do this, I recommend using the "support interface" setting in Cura with a support interface density of 70% or less in order to make the supports easier to remove from her cape. And do take care to avoid snapping her arm off, as it will be weakened due to being vertical.

Alternately, you could probably get good results by printing her upright.

The print in the photo was done on a Monoprice Mini Delta at .05mm layer height.
